THE PROJECT OBJECTIVES ARE: 1) TO TEST WHETHER OVERWINTERING MONARCH BUTTERFLIES SELECT A SUBSET OF
THE MICROCLIMATE CONDITIONS THAT ARE AVAILABLE IN OVERWINTERING GROVES. THIS WOULD BE ACCOMPLISHED
BY SHOWING THAT THE MICROCLIMATE CONDITIONS MONARCHS USE ARE A SUBSET, WITH SMALLER VARIANCE, OF THE
CONDITIONS AVAILABLE AT RANDOM UNOCCUPIED SITES WITHIN A GROVE. 2) TO THEN DEVELOP A QUANTITATIVE
CHARACTERIZATION OF THE MICROCLIMATE CONDITIONS SELECTED BY MONARCH BUTTERFLIES. 3) TO DEVELOP THAT
CHARACTERIZATION ACROSS A REPRESENTATIVE SET OF GROVES FROM ACROSS THE OVERWINTERING RANGE OF WESTERN
MONARCHS; AND 4) TO DEVELOP A PARAMETERIZED MODEL TO ASSESS MICROCLIMATE SUITABILITY BASED ON ALL
THE GROVES INCLUDED IN THE STUDY.

THE MANAGEMENT OBJECTIVES ARE: 1) TO PROVIDE MONARCH BUTTERFLY OVERWINTERING SITE MANAGERS,
USFWS, AND PARTNERS WITH A MODEL FOR ASSESSING MICROCLIMATE AT NOVEL GROVES, 2) TO PROVIDE LAND
MANAGERS AND PARTNERS WITH AN ANALYSIS OF THE CORRELATION BETWEEN MICROCLIMATE AND MICROHABITAT
PARAMETERS, SUCH THAT APPROPRIATE MICROCLIMATE OUTCOMES CAN BE OBTAINED THROUGH RESTORATION OF
MICROHABITAT CONDITIONS.
